Basic Education Minister Angie Motshekga on Monday briefed the media on the basic education sector’s response to the third wave of the Covid-19 pandemic currently sweeping the country. Motshekga announced that public schools will reopen on 19 July after President Cyril Ramaphosa announced on Sunday evening the country would move to level 4 lockdown, with all schools expected to close from Wednesday. ALSO READ: Level 4 adjustments: Here’s what you can and can’t do “By Wednesday, that’s the last day for pupils to be in schools. So, teaching will stop on Wednesday. Then we will use Thursday and Friday for teachers and managers to close the schools properly,” Motshekga said, speaking at Seemahale Secondary School in Botshabelo, Free State. Minister Angie Motshekga: schools will reopen on 19 July.
Schools must make arrangements that for the remaining 3 days, learners still receive their meals. — Dep. Basic Education (@DBE_SA) June 28, 2021  The minister said the Council of Ministers of Education (CEM) met on Monday morning to deliberate on the country’s move to level 4 lockdown, which is set to last for two weeks. The Free State province is on course to complete its vaccine roll-out programme for educators and school staff by Friday. READ MORE: New regulations could see Malema and EFF imprisoned READ NEXT: Ramaphosa’s ‘lockdown nonsense regulations won’t stop us’ – Malema